'''Lemmons''', previously known as '''Gladsmuir House''' and currently as '''Gladsmuir''', was the name given by the writer [[Kingsley Amis]] (1922<U+2013>1995) and his second wife, novelist [[Elizabeth Jane Howard]] (1923<U+2013>2014), to their home on [[Monken Hadley Common|Hadley Common]], [[London Borough of Barnet|Barnet]], on the border of [[north London]] and [[Hertfordshire]].<ref name=Keulks2003p135>Gavin Keulks, ''Father and Son: Kingsley Amis, Martin Amis, and the British Novel Since 1950'', University of Wisconsin Press, 2003, p. 135.</ref> 

The couple bought the [[Georgian architecture|Georgian house]] and its three-acre garden in 1968 for <U+00A3>48,000 at auction, and lived there until 1976. The house, which dates to 1830, had been registered as a Grade II [[Listed building (United Kingdom)|listed building]] in 1949 under the name Gladsmuir House. Howard restored the house's previous name, Lemmons, although the next owners changed it again to Gladsmuir.<ref>Zachary Leader, ''The Life of Kingsley Amis'', Jonathan Cape, 2006, pp. 607, 617.
*For its previous name, see Keulks 2003, p. 135, and Leader 2006, p. 626.
*For the next owners changing it to Gladsmuir, see Ian Norrie, ''Barnet in old photographs'', A. Sutton, 1993, p. 113.</ref>

Amis and Howard lived at Lemmons with a variety of house guests and family members, including Philip Amis, [[Martin Amis]] and [[Sally Amis]], Amis's children. In 1972 the [[Poet Laureate of the United Kingdom|poet laureate]] [[Cecil Day-Lewis]] (1904<U+2013>1972), his wife, [[Jill Balcon]] (1925<U+2013>2009), and their children, [[Daniel Day-Lewis]] and [[Tamasin Day-Lewis]], stayed there when Cecil was dying of cancer.<ref name=Sansom>Ian Sansom, [http://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2010/apr/03/great-dynasties-day-lewis-amis "Great dynasties of the world: The Day-Lewises"], ''The Guardian'', 3 April 2010.</ref> He died in the house on 22 May 1972; his poem, ''At Lemmons'', is about the last weeks of his life there.<ref name=poem/> [[Ian Sansom]] writes that, for the brief period that the Amises, Day-Lewises and others were in residence, Lemmons became "the most brilliantly creative household in Britain."<ref name=Sansom/>

==Architecture==
Red-brick with a [[stucco]] trim, the house has [[Bay (architecture)|five-bays]], two-storeys, a central [[Doric order|Doric]] porch with [[Fluting (architecture)|fluted]] columns, and [[entablature]] with [[triglyph]]s. There are [[sash window]]s, two staircases, a later extension and a detached housekeeper's cottage, Gladsmuir Cottage.<ref name=listed>[http://list.english-heritage.org.uk/resultsingle.aspx?uid=1359075 "Gladsmuir"], English Heritage: "Circa 1830 Villa. Red brick with plot band, quoins and architraves of stucco. Low pitch slate roof with deep eaves on brackets. Two storeys, 5 windows, sashes with glazing bars. Central Doric porch with fluted columns and triglyph entablature. Panelled double doors. Good entrance hall, other interiors not seen."
*[http://www.britishlistedbuildings.co.uk/en-198900-gladsmuir-greater-london-authority "Gladsmuir"], britishlistedbuildings.co.uk: "Circa 1830 Villa. Red brick with plot band, quoins and architraves of stucco. Low pitch slate roof with deep eaves on brackets. Two storeys, 5 windows, sashes with glazing bars. Central Doric porch with fluted columns and triglyph entablature. Panelled double doors. Good entrance hall, other interiors not seen."
*T.F.T Baker et al (eds.), [http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=26963 "'Monken Hadley: Introduction'"], '' A History of the County of Middlesex'', Volume 5, 1976, pp. 260<U+2013>263: "South of the common, Lemmons, formerly Gladsmuir House, stands on the site of a house belonging to Henry Bellamy in 1584; the building, with a Doric porch, an extension to the east, and a room enriched with late 18th-century medallions, has been much altered since it was built by the Quilter family, which owned the property from 1736 to 1909."</ref> When the Amises lived there, the house had over 20 rooms, according to Martin Amis.<ref>Martin Amis, ''Experience: A Memoir'', Miramax, 2000, p. 184.</ref> There were eight bedrooms, three reception rooms, a large kitchen, an old barn that was itself a listed building, a conservatory and a gravel drive.<ref>Leader 2006, p. 622.</ref> One room contains late 18th-century [[Medaillon (architecture)|medallions]].<ref name=listed/>

There are cedar woods and a meadow in the three-acre garden, as well as a [[weathervane]] dating to 1775.<ref>Bridget Cherry, ''London: North'', Yale University Press, 1998, p. 186.
*For the woods and meadow, see Zachary 2006, p. 622.</ref> The house was registered as a Grade II [[Listed building (United Kingdom)|listed building]] in 1949 as Gladsmuir House, with the address listed as Hadley Wood Road.<ref name=listed/>

==Residents==
{{Quote box
 |border=1px
 |title = ''At Lemmons''
 |halign=center
 |quote = <poem>Round me all is amenity, a bloom of
Magnolia uttering its requiems,
A climate of acceptance.  Very well
I accept my weakness with my friends<U+2019>
Good natures sweetening each day my sick room.</poem>
 |source= <U+2014> [[Cecil Day-Lewis]], 1972
 |align = right
 |width = 40%
