 |bgcolor = #F8F8FF
 |title_bg =
 |quoted = true
 }}
The land and an earlier house were owned by Henry Bellamy in 1584. The Quilter family owned it from 1736 to 1909, and built the current house around 1830.<ref name=listed/>

Kingsley Amis and Elizabeth Howard lived there from 1968 to 1976, for part of the time with Howard's brother Colin, and her mother, Katherine ("Kit"). The artists Sargy Mann and Terry Raybauld lived there too, as did Amis's children, Philip, Martin and Sally, when not at school, and the housekeeper Mrs. Uniacke.<ref>[http://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2010/apr/03/great-dynasties-day-lewis-amis Sansom (''Guardian'')], 3 April 2010; Leader 2006, pp. 630, 668.</ref> 

Kingsley Amis wrote several novels at Lemmons <U+2013> ''[[The Green Man]]'' (1969), ''Girl, 20'' (1971), ''The Riverside Villas Murder'' (1973) and ''Ending Up'' (1974) <U+2013> while Howard wrote ''Something in Disguise'' (1969), and Martin Amis wrote ''[[Dead Babies (novel)|Dead Babies]]'' (1975).<ref>Leader 2006, p. 633; Keulks 2003, p. 136; Amis 2000, pp. 184, 349.</ref>

House guests included the poet [[Philip Larkin]] (1922<U+2013>1985), writers [[Tina Brown]] and [[Paul Johnson (writer)|Paul Johnson]], the literary agent [[Pat Kavanagh]] (1940<U+2013>2008) and the psychiatrist James Durham, Kavanagh's partner at the time.<ref>Leader 2006, pp. 616, 631.</ref> Howard's mother died there in March 1972.<ref name=Keulks2003p135/> Later that spring, when he was dying of cancer, the poet laureate Cecil Day-Lewis stayed at Lemmons for five weeks, along with his wife, Jill Balcon, and their children, Daniel and Tamasin.<ref name=Sansom/> He wrote a poem about the house, ''At Lemmons'', shortly before his death there in May 1972.<ref name=poem>Cecil-Day Lewis, ''The Complete Poems'', Stanford University Press, 1992; see [http://www.cday-lewis.co.uk/#/at-lemmons/4525577835 "At Lemmons"], www.cday-lewis.co.uk.
*Leader 2006, pp. 630<U+2013>631.</ref>

The house was featured in June 1976 in an advertisement in ''[[Woman's Journal]]'' for wallpaper by [[Arthur Sanderson & Sons]]; Gavin Keulks reports that the ad read: "Very Sanderson, Very Amis."<ref>Keulks 2003, p. 284, note 6, citing Ian Woodward, "A Lovely Couple," ''Woman's Journal'', June 1976, pp. 19<U+2013>21.</ref> Amis and Howard sold the house shortly after this, moving to Gardnor House in Flask Walk, [[Hampstead]], London NW3; Amis was apparently tired of living so far from central London.<ref>Leader 2006, p. 667.</ref> As of 2014 the Hadley Trust, a grant-making charity, is registered at the house.<ref>[http://www.charityperformance.com/charity-details.php?id=13974 The Hadley Trust], Charity Performance, DG Publishing.</ref>

